Philippines Stock Movers: PLDT, Globe, Megaworld, Robinsons Land

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-06-21T04:28:06Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-21/manila-electric-megaworld-vista-philippine-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the noon close in  Manila .  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 1.4 percent to
4,211.81, snapping a two-day loss. Financial markets were shut
for a holiday yesterday.  Telecom Companies:  Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co. (TEL) 
,  Globe Telecom Inc. (GLO)  . Philippine Long Distance,
the nation’s biggest phone company, advanced 5.5 percent to
2,322 pesos, the sharpest gain since March 30. Globe climbed 3.8
percent to 875 pesos, the steepest advance since May 11.  The Appeals Court dismissed a rival’s complaint and upheld
a regulator’s 2005 decision to award 3G mobile-phone service
licenses to the two companies, BusinessWorld reported, citing a
decision by Associate Justice Mario Guarina III, who couldn’t be
reached for comment at his office.  Banco de Oro Unibank Inc. (BDO)  , the largest Philippine
bank by assets, jumped 3.9 percent to 53.80 pesos, the sharpest
gain since Dec. 2, after the company said it had “submitted an
expression of interest” in Philippine Bank of Communications,
which is being sold.  Energy Development Corp. (EDC)   climbed 1.9 percent to
6.52 pesos, the sharpest advance since May 31, after the power
producer obtained a $175 million loan to refinance existing debt
due in June 2013 and said it may recover a 1.8 billion-peso
annual revenue loss caused by the rehabilitation of a power
plant.  Megaworld Corp. (MEG)  , a property developer, gained 5.3
percent to 2 pesos, the sharpest gain since April 4. Megaworld
will spend 25 billion pesos ($573 million) on projects this
year, the company said in an e-mailed statement. The company and
its units sold 17 billion pesos worth of real-estate projects in
the first five months of this year, it said.  Robinsons Land Corp. (RLC)  , the second-largest shopping
mall operator, jumped 4.7 percent to 11.70 pesos, the steepest
gain since April 5. The developer is providing more than 20,000
square meters of new  office space  in its shopping malls for
providers of outsourced business services, BusinessWorld
reported, citing a company statement.  To contact the reporter on this story:
